  "slug": "christmas-cake-last-minute",
  "title": "Last-minute Christmas cake",
  "subtitle": "A Christmas fruit cake that can be made and iced in the same week, skipping the traditional months of maturing.",
  "excerpt": "Traditional Christmas cake is made weeks or months in advance and fed with brandy through the autumn. This version is made and decorated in the same week. Soaking the dried fruit overnight in orange juice and brandy compensates for the missing maturation time. The result is a moist, well-flavoured cake that tastes properly festive without the forward planning.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Traditional British Christmas cake descends from the plum cake tradition documented in seventeenth-century cookbooks, evolving into the spiced fruit cake form recognisable today by the mid-nineteenth century. Mrs Beeton's 'Book of Household Management' (1861) includes a Christmas cake designed for long keeping. The 'last-minute' approach of overnight fruit soaking has become widely published since the 1990s as a practical adaptation for time-limited cooks. The overnight orange juice soak is a technique used by food writers including Nigella Lawson and Delia Smith in various Christmas baking guides.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Traditional Christmas cake is made in October or November and fed weekly with brandy until December. This version takes the same ingredients and compresses the timing. The fruit soaks overnight in orange juice and a generous slug of brandy, and much of what the long maturing period achieves in flavour is replicated in that soak. It is a proper Christmas cake, not a simplified one.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The baking is slow: 2.5 hours at 140°C fan. Line the tin generously and wrap the outside in a double layer of newspaper or brown paper tied with string, which slows the heat at the edges and prevents the outside cooking before the centre.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "infoPanel",
        "attrs": {
          "body": "Long-baked fruit cakes burn at the outside edge before the centre is cooked if the tin is not insulated. Wrap the outside of the tin with a double layer of newspaper or brown paper tied with string, and place a folded newspaper on the oven shelf below the cake. Alternatively, reduce the temperature by a further 10 degrees and extend the baking time by 20 minutes.",
          "tone": "info",
          "title": "Protecting the tin"
        }
      },
      {
